  "how-to-check-florida-roofing-license": {
    title: "How to Tell If a Florida Roofer Is Actually Legal (Before You Give Them a Dime)",
    metaTitle: "Checking Florida Roofing Licenses: A Jacksonville Homeowner's Guide",
    excerpt: "Don't get stuck with a bad roof or a lawsuit. Here's exactly how to check a Florida roofing contractor's license and insurance in under 5 minutes.",
    content: `
      <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6">Every year after hurricane season, Jacksonville neighborhoods get flooded with trucks from out of state. Some of these contractors are legitimate. Many are not. And by the time you figure out the difference, they've already cashed your check and moved on to the next zip code.</p>

      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">In Florida, the rules are strict. To be a legitimate <strong>roofing contractor license Florida</strong> holder, you have to pass a state exam, carry specific insurance, and register with the Department of Business and Professional Regulation (DBPR). But here's the thing: scammers know most homeowners won't bother to check.</p>

      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-8">This guide will show you exactly how to verify a roofer's credentials in under 5 minutes, so you never have to wonder if you're dealing with a professional or a con artist.</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">Step 1: Get Their License Number (Not Just Their Word)</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">A legitimate contractor will have their license number on their truck, their business card, and their contract. If you have to ask for it multiple times, that's your first red flag.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">Florida roofing licenses start with "CCC" (for Certified) or "RC" (for Registered). Write this number down. You'll need it for the next step.</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">Step 2: Verify on the DBPR Website</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">Go to <a href="https://www.myfloridalicense.com/wl11.asp" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-primary hover:underline">MyFloridaLicense.com</a> and enter the license number. You'll see:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 text-gray-600 space-y-2">
        <li>The contractor's legal name and business name</li>
        <li>Whether their license is "Current, Active" (the only status you want to see)</li>
        <li>Any complaints or disciplinary actions</li>
        <li>When the license expires</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">If the license shows "Delinquent," "Suspended," or doesn't exist at all, end the conversation immediately.</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">Why "Registered" vs. "Certified" Matters for a Florida Roofing Contractor</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">This is where it gets important for Jacksonville homeowners:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 text-gray-600 space-y-2">
        <li><strong>Certified Contractors (CCC):</strong> Can work anywhere in Florida. They passed the state exam and meet all state requirements.</li>
        <li><strong>Registered Contractors (RC):</strong> Can only work in specific counties where they've registered. They're licensed locally but haven't taken the state certification exam.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">Both are legal, but if someone with an "RC" license from Tampa shows up in Jacksonville, they're working outside their jurisdiction. That's a problem for you if something goes wrong.</p>

      <div class="bg-primary/10 border-l-4 border-primary p-6 my-8 rounded-r-lg">
        <p class="font-bold text-secondary mb-2">Gimo's Take:</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700">"I've seen so many homeowners in Jacksonville get burned by 'tailgate' contractors who disappear after the first rain. If their license number isn't on their truck, keep walking. And if they pressure you to sign today because of a 'storm damage deadline,' that's almost always a scam. Real contractors don't need to pressure you."</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">Step 3: Verify Their Insurance (Yes, Actually Call)</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">A license isn't enough. You need to confirm they carry:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 text-gray-600 space-y-2">
        <li><strong>General Liability Insurance:</strong> Covers damage to your property</li>
        <li><strong>Workers' Compensation:</strong> Covers injuries to workers on your property</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">Ask for a Certificate of Insurance and actually call the insurance company to verify it's current. Scammers have been known to provide fake certificates or policies that lapsed months ago.</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">Step 4: Check for Complaints</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">Beyond the DBPR website, search for:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 text-gray-600 space-y-2">
        <li>Better Business Bureau complaints</li>
        <li>Google Reviews (look for patterns in negative reviews)</li>
        <li>Local news stories (search their company name + "lawsuit" or "complaint")</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">Understanding Roofing Contractor Requirements in Florida</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">Florida has some of the strictest <strong>roofing contractor requirements</strong> in the country, and for good reason. Our roofs take a beating from hurricanes, tropical storms, and relentless sun.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">Legal requirements include:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 text-gray-600 space-y-2">
        <li>Passing a state-approved examination</li>
        <li>Minimum $300,000 in general liability insurance</li>
        <li>Workers' compensation coverage for all employees</li>
        <li>Financial responsibility requirements</li>
        <li>Continuing education to maintain the license</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">When a contractor cuts corners on licensing, they're telling you they'll cut corners on your roof too.</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">Red Flags That Should End the Conversation</h2>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 text-gray-600 space-y-2">
        <li>"We're only in town this week" - Legitimate contractors have permanent local operations</li>
        <li>"We can start today if you sign now" - High-pressure tactics are a scam signature</li>
        <li>"Pay in full upfront" - Never pay more than 10-20% as a deposit</li>
        <li>"We'll handle everything with your insurance" - You should always be involved in insurance claims</li>
        <li>"We don't do written contracts" - Every job needs a detailed written contract</li>
        <li>No physical address or only a P.O. Box - Real businesses have real locations</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">The Bottom Line</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">Checking a contractor's credentials takes 5 minutes. Dealing with a bad roof job or a legal nightmare can take years and cost thousands. Do your homework before signing anything.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">At Gimo's Roofing, we're happy to provide our license number, insurance certificates, and references before you even schedule an estimate. That's how it should work. If a contractor makes you feel weird for asking, find someone who doesn't. <a href="/about" class="text-primary hover:underline font-semibold">Learn more about our licensed Jacksonville roofing contractor</a> credentials.</p>
    `,
