  "questions-to-ask-roofing-contractor": {
    title: "The 10 Questions I Wish Every Homeowner Would Ask Me During an Estimate",
    metaTitle: "Questions to Ask a Roofing Contractor | Hiring Tips for 2025",
    excerpt: "Don't hire a roofer based on price alone. Use these critical questions to ask a roofing contractor to make sure your home is in the right hands.",
    content: `
      <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6">Most people don't know the right <strong>questions to ask a roofing contractor</strong>, so they just look at the bottom number. I get it. Roofing isn't something you think about until you need it. But the lowest bid often costs you the most in the long run.</p>

      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-8">After years of providing estimates in Jacksonville, I've put together the questions that separate informed homeowners from those who end up calling us to fix someone else's mess.</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">Question 1: "Can I See Your Florida Roofing License?"</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">This should be automatic. The license number should be on their truck, their card, and their estimate. If they hesitate, thank them for their time and show them the door.</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">Question 2: "What's Your Workers' Comp Policy Number?"</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">If a worker gets hurt on your property and the contractor doesn't have workers' comp, guess who gets sued? You. Ask for the policy number and verify it's active.</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">Question 3: "Who Will Actually Be Doing the Work?"</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">Some companies are "brokers" who sell jobs and subcontract everything. Others have their own crews. Neither is automatically bad, but you should know:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 text-gray-600 space-y-2">
        <li>Will the person giving me this estimate be at my house during the job?</li>
        <li>How long has your crew been working together?</li>
        <li>Are your workers employees or subcontractors?</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="bg-primary/10 border-l-4 border-primary p-6 my-8 rounded-r-lg">
        <p class="font-bold text-secondary mb-2">Gimo's Take:</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700">"When you're learning how to choose the right roofing contractor, watch how they treat your questions. A good contractor welcomes them. A shady one gets annoyed or evasive. Your gut feeling matters here."</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">Question 4: "What Happens If It Rains During the Job?"</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">In Florida, afternoon storms are a given. A professional contractor has a plan. They should be able to tell you exactly how they protect your home if they need to stop mid-job.</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">Question 5: "What's Included in This Price?"</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">Cheap estimates often hide costs. Make sure you understand:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 text-gray-600 space-y-2">
        <li>Is tear-off of the old roof included, or are they going over it?</li>
        <li>Are they replacing damaged decking? How much is included before extra charges?</li>
        <li>What about flashing, vents, and pipe boots?</li>
        <li>Who handles the permit and inspections?</li>
        <li>Is debris removal and dumpster rental included?</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">Question 6: "What Materials Are You Using?"</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">Understanding <strong>how to choose the right roofing contractor</strong> means understanding what they're putting on your house. Ask for specifics:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 text-gray-600 space-y-2">
        <li>Brand and product line of shingles (e.g., GAF Timberline HDZ, Owens Corning Duration)</li>
        <li>What type of underlayment?</li>
        <li>What ice and water shield are they using around penetrations?</li>
        <li>What's the ventilation plan?</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">Question 7: "What Warranties Do I Get?"</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">There are two types of warranties, and you need both:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 text-gray-600 space-y-2">
        <li><strong>Manufacturer Warranty:</strong> Covers defects in the shingles themselves. Length depends on the product (25-50 years typical).</li>
        <li><strong>Workmanship Warranty:</strong> Covers the contractor's installation work. This is where companies differ. Get the length and terms in writing.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">Question 8: "Can I See Some Recent Projects Nearby?"</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">A contractor who's been working in Jacksonville should have no problem pointing you to a recent job in your area. Bonus points if they can connect you with a homeowner reference.</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">Question 9: "What's Your Payment Schedule?"</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">Red flags:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 text-gray-600 space-y-2">
        <li>Demanding full payment upfront</li>
        <li>Cash-only requirements</li>
        <li>No written contract</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">A normal payment schedule is a small deposit (10-20%) with the balance due upon completion. Some contractors take payment at material delivery. Get it in writing either way.</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">Question 10: "What Happens If There's a Problem After You're Done?"</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">Ask about their callback policy. How quickly do they respond to warranty issues? Is there a different number to call? What's considered warranty work vs. new damage?</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">Bonus: Trust Your Instincts</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">Beyond these questions, pay attention to how the contractor conducts themselves:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 text-gray-600 space-y-2">
        <li>Did they show up on time for the estimate?</li>
        <li>Did they actually get on the roof or just look from the ground?</li>
        <li>Did they explain things in plain language?</li>
        <li>Did they pressure you to sign immediately?</li>
        <li>Did their estimate come in writing with itemized details?</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">How to Choose a Good Commercial Roofing Contractor</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-4">If you're a business owner or property manager, the stakes are even higher. <strong>How to choose a good commercial roofing contractor</strong> involves additional considerations:</p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-6 mb-6 text-gray-600 space-y-2">
        <li><strong>Experience with your roof type:</strong> Commercial roofs (TPO, EPDM, modified bitumen) require specialized knowledge. Ask for commercial-specific references.</li>
        <li><strong>Ability to work around operations:</strong> Can they complete work during off-hours or in phases to minimize business disruption?</li>
        <li><strong>Maintenance programs:</strong> Do they offer ongoing maintenance contracts? Commercial roofs need regular inspections.</li>
        <li><strong>Project management capabilities:</strong> Large commercial projects need proper coordination. Ask about their project management process.</li>
        <li><strong>Insurance limits:</strong> Commercial projects require higher liability limits. Verify their coverage matches your needs.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">Learn more about our <a href="/services/commercial-roofing" class="text-primary hover:underline font-semibold">commercial roofing services</a> for Jacksonville businesses.</p>

      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-secondary mt-10 mb-4">The Bottom Line</h2>
      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">Knowing <strong>how to hire a roofing contractor</strong> is about more than just a quote; it's about peace of mind. The right contractor welcomes your questions, provides clear answers, and never makes you feel rushed or pressured.</p>

      <p class="text-gray-600 mb-6">We're happy to answer all of these questions and more during your free estimate. That's what professionals do. Ready to get started? <a href="/services/roof-replacement" class="text-primary hover:underline font-semibold">Get affordable roof replacement estimates</a> today.</p>
    `,
